    "created_at": "2016-12-22T01:01:51Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-12-22T01:01:51Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "I'm seeing similar hangs with grpc 1.0.0. Basically, in situations where node would normally coredump, it now hangs indefinitely if the `grpc` module has been imported. However, this seems to be fixed in grpc 1.0.1 (released on 2016-10-27).\r\n\r\n@mikelehen: Can you verify if the hang you saw is fixed with grpc 1.0.1, too?\r\n\r\n@murgatroid99: Do you know which specific commits would have fixed this?\r\n\r\nHere's simple way to reproduce it. Run this command and observe a `RangeError` crash:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ node -e 'require(\"grpc\"); function crash() { crash(); } crash();'\r\n[eval]:1\r\nrequire(\"grpc\"); function crash() { crash(); } crash();\r\n                               ^\r\n\r\nRangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:32)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n    at crash ([eval]:1:37)\r\n```\r\n\r\nWith grpc 1.0.0, adding `--abort-on-uncaught-exception` results in a hang:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ node --abort-on-uncaught-exception -e 'require(\"grpc\"); function crash() { crash(); } crash();'\r\n<error>\r\n\r\nFROM\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe know this is caused by grpc because removing `require(\"grpc\")` results in a coredump as expected:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ node --abort-on-uncaught-exception -e 'function crash() { crash(); } crash();'\r\n<error>\r\n\r\nFROM\r\nIllegal instruction (core dumped)\r\n```\r\n\r\nWith grpc 1.0.1, `--abort-on-uncaught-exception` results in a coredump as expected:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ node --abort-on-uncaught-exception -e 'require(\"grpc\"); function crash() { crash(); } crash();'\r\n<error>\r\n\r\nFROM\r\nIllegal instruction (core dumped)\r\n```\r\n\r\nI've verified this with both node 4.7.0 and 6.9.2. (I couldn't get grpc to compile with 7.3.0.)"
